In article <268f3b$ar5@moonpie.cs.umd.edu>, Christopher Biow (biow@cs.umd.edu) writes:
>In article <Sep03.155808.59281@yuma.ACNS.ColoState.EDU> holland@CS.ColoState.EDU (douglas craig holland) writes:
>
>>My question is why do they even have to break the launch codes, when
>>they could simply hotwire the nukes?  Why bother to pick the lock when
>>it is quicker just to break it?
>
>To stretch the analogy, one must not so much destroy the lock as replace
>it with another lock that will operate the door. The Permissive Action
>Link is built so that it is more difficult to hotwire it than it is
>to build a new detonator. 
>
>A fair amount of remanufacturing must be done to bypass/replace
>the PAL. That work, it is estimated, would take the Ukrainians
>a few months to accomplish, should they decide to do so. They
>could probably produce crude plutonium bombs faster than that,
>but would have to provide their own delivery systems.
>
>So the crypto part of it makes the difference between using them
>off-the-shelf and running a mini-Manhattan project to rebuild them.
>
>Kravchuck, the Ukrainian Prime Minister, just agreed to sell "his"
>nukes to the Russians for debt forgiveness. The Ukrainian parliament
>may not agree. Stay tuned.
>
>
>

Why don't we (the U.S.) just offer to _buy_ the damned things?  *I'd*
certainly be willing to pony up a few bucks extra for it..... 

